The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, July 20, 2004 				 HDFC net up 22% to Rs 205 cr
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT				 	 Parekh: Home truths																								Mumbai, July 19: Housing Development Finance Corporation Ltd (HDFC) has reported a 22 per cent rise in net profit at Rs 204.62 crore for the first quarter ended June 30, 2004 compared with Rs 167.76 crore in the corresponding previous quarter. The company notched up these figures after making a higher tax provision of Rs 43.07 crore against Rs 37.44 crore in the year-ago period.																								HDFC said, as of June 30, total assets stood at Rs 33,748.92 crore, up 26 per cent against Rs 26,782.69 crore in the comparable previous period.																								The housing finance major approved Rs 3,566.79 crore worth of loans during the quarter, up 31 per cent against Rs 2,731.43 crore in the corresponding period last year. Loan disbursements amounted to Rs 2,690.45 crore, up from Rs 2,091.82 crore last year.																								Tax incentives, stable property prices and increased income levels continue to make housing more affordable. Retail growth continued to be robust as a result of an increased network of offices and intensified marketing efforts, HDFC said.																								As on June 30, the loan portfolio, including outstanding loans, deposits and investments in preference shares and debentures for financing real estate-related projects, amounted to Rs 30,246 crore against Rs 23,778 crore a year earlier.																								During the current fiscal, loans drawn from commercial banks amounted to Rs 2,833 crore. HDFC also raised Rs 900 crore through private placements of non-convertible debentures. The corporation availed of Rs 250 crore as refinance from National Housing Bank (NHB) during the reporting quarter.																								Its capital adequacy ratio stood at 14.7 per cent of the risk-weighted assets.																								Speaking at the companys annual general meeting here today, Deepak Parekh, chairman and managing director of HDFC, said with effect from March 31, 2005 NHB has stipulated that an asset will be classified as a non-performing one if the interest or instalment is overdue for a period of 90 days. 																								NHB has permitted housing finance companies to phase out the additional provisioning over a period of three years commencing from March 31, 2005 with a minimum of 20 per cent additional provisioning being required to be made each year, he said.																								Your corporation has already made the necessary provision in terms of systems, monitoring mechanisms and manpower to comply with the new norms, he told shareholders.																								At the meeting, HDFC placed an enabling resolution to raise up to an aggregate amount of $500 million by issuing foreign currency bonds and other such securities. Parekh clarified that raising of any international fund is subject to a change in the current policy and after obtaining the requisite regulatory approvals. 																								He pointed out the resolution is only to get shareholders approvals in place and that no terms or conditions have been finalised by HDFC on raising international funds. 																								Such funds will be raised only subject to regulatory approvals and if market conditions are conducive.IPCL net zooms 215%																								Indian Petrochemicals Corporation Ltd (IPCL) has posted a 215 per cent rise in net profit to Rs 123 crore for the first quarter ended June 30 against Rs 39 crore in the same period last year.																								Gross turnover was up 25 per cent at Rs 3,302 crore against Rs 2,633 crore. 
